[SkillPath "practice_deals/100_notrump"]
[Student "S"]
{Partner's 2\C is Stayman convention. With no 4-card Major suit your response is 2\D. Partner now bids 2NT.  

Partner's 2\C is Stayman convention. With no 4-card Major suit your response is 2\D. Partner now bids 2NT. 

The 2NT bid is invitational, asking you to bid game with a maximum, pass with a minimum. You have 17 points so you bid 3NT.

North plays 3NT. East leads the \S7. You put on dummy's \SJ, but West wins the \SA then continues with the \S9. Do you play your \SK now?

Winner List: \S = 1 : \H = 3 : \D = 0 : \C = 2 :: Total = 6

You need 3 more tricks, and they must come from \Ds. So you must drive out the \DA. The problem is that when the defenders win the \DA they may also take 4 \S tricks.

This is another case where you should hold up. Allow EW to win the second trick and take your  \SK only at trick #3. 

Now you drive out the \DA. If East has it and also started with 5 \Ss you will go down. But if West has the \DA you will make the contract no matter how \Ss split.

If you win the second \S West will still have a \S when he wins the \DA.

But if you hold up your \SK West will have no \S to put his partner in with. }
[Play "W"]S7

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:K85.A2.A73.AKQ72 J743.KJ95.Q95.85 Q9.843.KJT82.JT4 AT62.QT76.64.963"]
[Declarer "E"]
