[SkillPath "practice_deals/100_notrump"]
[Student "S"]
{Even if you wanted to show your \D suit how would you do it? If you bid 3\D it would be a transfer and if you bid 4\D you would have bypassed 3NT, your probable best contract.

But you didn't want to bid them anyway, you just wanted to bid 3NT, right?

The contract would be 3NT played by West.

South leads \H5, North plays the \HQ.

The first thing you need to decide is whether to hold up on the \H.

Winner List: \S = 0 : \H = 1 : \D = 2 : \C = 5 :: Total = 8

First decide the holdup question. South led the \H5 and you can see the \H4, \H3 and \H2. Assuming South led fourth down he must have only a 4-card suit since there are no cards he could have lower than the \H5. With \Hs splitting 4-4 a holdup would do no good, and isn't necessary anyway.

So take the \HA. Then what? 

You COULD try the \D finesse. Even if it loses it would establish several \D winners. However, if the defenders win just 1 \D trick they will quickly grab their 3 \H tricks and their \SA and put you down 1. 

This is why it is important to  You need just one additional winner and all you have to do to get it is play a \S honor.

When you can see all four hands, including the location of the \DQ, it kind of makes you wished you had finessed and gotten all those overtricks.

Good Bridge players like to take tricks, but they are not greedy.}
[Play "W"]H5

